<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its basionym 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Hypoxylaceae" genus="Sphaeria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sphaeria stilbostoma" order="Xylariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Sphaeria stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(α 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">papula</emphasis>
) were mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tulasne, LR" journalOrPublisher="Contributii Botanice Cluj" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B48" refString="Tulasne, LR, 1856. Note sur l'appareil reproducteur multiple des Hypoxylees (DC.) ou Pyrenomycetes (Fr.). Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, ser. 4, 5: 107-118." title="Note sur l'appareil reproducteur multiple des Hypoxylees (DC.) ou Pyrenomycetes (Fr.). Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, ser. 4, 5: 107 - 118." year="1856">Tulasne (1856)</bibRefCitation>
, but the combination was invalid due to the lack of a generic diagnosis; it was, however, validated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Tulasne, LR" journalOrPublisher="Contributii Botanice Cluj" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B49" refString="Tulasne, LR, Tulasne, C, 1863. Selecta Fungorum Carpologia: Xylariei-Valsei-Sphaeriei. 2. Imperial Typograph, Paris." title="Selecta Fungorum Carpologia: Xylariei-Valsei-Sphaeriei. 2. Imperial Typograph, Paris." year="1863">Tulasne and Tulasne (1863)</bibRefCitation>
. According to Ibai Olariaga, who examined the type in UPS, there are 3 scalps of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bark containing many clustered perithecia with black ostiolar necks erumpent through a white disc; neither asci nor spores were found, but brown 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
are present abundantly. As the type collection was distributed in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Fries’">Fries'</normalizedToken>
Scleromyceti Sueciae no. 145, we here lectotypify the species with the copy preserved in UPS, which we epitypify with a recent well-developed collection for which a culture and sequence data are available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
Several asexual morph names have been linked with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconium bicolor" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconium bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
predates 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but there is no material extant in B, thus it cannot be checked; also 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but not 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was given as host in the protologue. In addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a well-known and well-defined name for the generic type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The second name is 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconium betulinum" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="betulinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconium betulinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is clearly a later synonym upon our examination of type material. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Corda" authorityYear="1839" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconium elevatum" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="elevatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconium elevatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is another synonym. We have, however, not seen type material of this taxon, but the description and illustrations in 
<bibRefCitation author="Corda, ACJ" journalOrPublisher="Commentario della Societa Crittogamologica Italiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B6" refString="Corda, ACJ, 1839. Icones Fungorum hucusque Cognitorum 3: i-vi, 1-55, plates 1-9. J.G. Calve, Prague." title="Icones Fungorum hucusque Cognitorum 3: i-vi, 1 - 55, plates 1 - 9. J. G. Calve, Prague." year="1839">Corda (1839)</bibRefCitation>
are conclusive. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very common fungus on birch throughout the northern hemisphere and likely the most conspicuous species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to the shiny white discs of both morphs, contrasting the dark conidial deposits. In older specimens, the latter may have olivaceous tones, but much less conspicuously than with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. larissae" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="larissae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. larissae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species differs also in a broad light zone present on its conidia. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 115" authorityYear="1863" baseAuthorityName="Fr.: Fr." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis stilbostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="stilbostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis stilbostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was already cultured by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1926.12020516" author="Wehmeyer, LE" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="257 - 273" refId="B63" refString="Wehmeyer, LE, 1926b. Cultural life histories of Melanconis and Pseudovalsa. Mycologia 18: 257 - 273, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1926.12020516" title="Cultural life histories of Melanconis and Pseudovalsa." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1926.12020516" volume="18" year="1926 b">Wehmeyer (1926b)</bibRefCitation>
on birch twigs from material, whose ascospore measurements were (13-)15-18 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, corresponding to those of 
<bibRefCitation author="Barr, ME" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia Memoirs" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 232" refId="B1" refString="Barr, ME, 1978. The Diaporthales of North America. Mycologia Memoirs 7: 1 - 232" title="The Diaporthales of North America." volume="7" year="1978">Barr (1978</bibRefCitation>
: 12-18.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.5-8(-9) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Wehmeyer, LE" journalOrPublisher="University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B64" refString="Wehmeyer, LE, 1941. A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania. University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series 14: 1 - 161" title="A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania." volume="14" year="1941">Wehmeyer (1941)</bibRefCitation>
gave (13-)15-19(-23) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(5-)6-7.5(-9) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
for ascospores, which is in accordance with our measurements ((13.7-)16-19(-23) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.7-)6.5-8.5(-9.7) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
); 
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 242" refId="B24" refString="Kobayashi, T, 1970. Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories. Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro 226: 1 - 242" title="Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories." volume="226" year="1970">Kobayashi (1970)</bibRefCitation>
measured 13-25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, mostly 15-20 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B9" refString="Fan, XL, Du, Z, Liang, Y, Tian, CM, 2016. Melanconis (Melanconidaceae) associated with Betula spp. in China. Mycological Progress 15: 40. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" title="Melanconis (Melanconidaceae) associated with Betula spp. in China. Mycological Progress 15: 40." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" year="2016">Fan et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
gave (19-)21.5-23.5(-25) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(6-)7-8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, which is slightly larger. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wehmeyer, LE" journalOrPublisher="University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B64" refString="Wehmeyer, LE, 1941. A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania. University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series 14: 1 - 161" title="A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania." volume="14" year="1941">Wehmeyer (1941)</bibRefCitation>
noted for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
from culture and exsiccata mostly 10-16 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
and 6.5-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-2.5 for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="β-conidia">β-conidia</normalizedToken>
in culture; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barr, ME" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia Memoirs" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 232" refId="B1" refString="Barr, ME, 1978. The Diaporthales of North America. Mycologia Memoirs 7: 1 - 232" title="The Diaporthales of North America." volume="7" year="1978">Barr (1978)</bibRefCitation>
found only 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
and measured 9-16.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, which is in accordance with our observations from Europe (see above). Asian authors gave 9-16.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 242" refId="B24" refString="Kobayashi, T, 1970. Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories. Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro 226: 1 - 242" title="Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories." volume="226" year="1970">Kobayashi 1970</bibRefCitation>
) and (8.5-)9-14.5(-16) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.5-)5-6(-6.5) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" refId="B9" refString="Fan, XL, Du, Z, Liang, Y, Tian, CM, 2016. Melanconis (Melanconidaceae) associated with Betula spp. in China. Mycological Progress 15: 40. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" title="Melanconis (Melanconidaceae) associated with Betula spp. in China. Mycological Progress 15: 40." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-016-1163-2" year="2016">Fan et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
) for 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
, but, in some collections, they also found cylindrical to allantoid, unicellular, hyaline 
<normalizedToken originalValue="β-conidia">β-conidia</normalizedToken>
, 9-11.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 242" refId="B24" refString="Kobayashi, T, 1970. Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories. Bulletin of the Government Forest Experimental Station Meguro 226: 1 - 242" title="Taxonomic studies of Japanese Diaporthaceae with special reference to their life-histories." volume="226" year="1970">Kobayashi 1970</bibRefCitation>
